{"/service/ndnp/nvln/batch_nvln_jackpot_ver01/data/sn84001718/00279554395/1923113001/0206.xml":{"full_text":"VOhljyiL (,^DNjgVlLLE, DOUGLAS COUNTY, NEVADA, FRIDAY MORNING, NOVEMBER 30, 1923 NUMBER FORTY-FOUR\nrange control\nIS INVESTIGATED\nNeeded Changes In\nRules Will Help\nStock Men\n\"Plans for wiyking out a definite\nsystem or range control, the secur\ning of the appointment of a range\nspecialist for the eleven Western\nstates In the near future and the\nassembling of material for the pub\nlishing of a range hand book fey\ncounty agricultural agents were\namong tiie things accomplished at\nthe Western States agricultural and j\nlive stock conference with heads of\nthe bureaus of the department of\nagriculture at Kort Collins,\" said\nCecil W Creel, chief of agricultural\nextension work in Nevada, upon his I\nreturn, report the Gazette.\n\u25a0'Representatives of the eleven\nWestern range states were present,\u201d\nhe continued, \"and the Idea was at\nonce advanced to get down to\nfundamentals facts upo.n which a\nprogram could be worked out for the\nbenefit of the live stock men who j\nrange their flocks and herds on the\npublic domain. Working along Ibis\nline, we decided among the needs,\nof laying stress upon the following\nprojects:\n\"First Increasing the percentage\nof calf anil lamb crops.\n\"Second Establishing better feed\ning and grazing practices.\n\"Third Instituting Improved breed\ning methrvds.\n\"Fourth\u2014Saving young animals.\n\"Fifth\u2014Keeping records of the\nranch business to determine opera\ntion costs.\n\"It was recommended that the\nabove prrvgram cover a period of\nseven years and that each state es\ntarnish definite goals. For the carry\ning out of the above program recom\nmended the use of all existing Htate\nanil federal experimental results as\ndemonstration material; use of suc\ncessful ranches as demonstration\npoints; utilization of other special\nists qualified to give assistance on\nrange problems; employment of\nboy's and girls' clubs as a demon\nstration agency; preparation and\nutilization of exhibits as teaching\nagencies; publication of pamphlets\nund other publicity agencies; con\nducting tours to public and private\ndemonstrations of approved prac\ntices; e.-lahllshlng personal contacts\nwith Individual stockmen and with\ngrazing; live stock and similar as\nsociations\n\"Our first work was to ascertain\nthe needs In the range stales and\nthis wan arrived at from reports glv-j\nen by range specialists who had\nbeen appointed fo gather data From\nthis we found that In ten Western\nstates, excepting Texas, which has j\nsolved the range problem, that there\nwere approximately 650,000.000 acres!\nof land which can probably never be;\nutilized for any other purpose other\nthan for ranging sheep and cattle\nOf this amount we found 628,000,000 j\nacres are In public domain and not\nunder adequate control. The re\nmainder is either In national forests\nor <\\wned privately. This established\nthe fact that the range problem and\nIts management was one of the out\nstanding problems for the growth\nand development of Western slates\nand with these facts as -a ground\nfoundathyi the problem of the range\nwere discussed.\n\"The question of range control was j\none on which no specific recom- j\ninendatlnns were made, but all rec\nognized that there should be s<\\nio\nsystem of control whereby the runge j\ncould be made to produce more,\nwould not be overstryked, rodents\ncontrolled which destroy feed, water\ndeveloped So that Stock could be\ngrazed on ranges now useless be\ncause o,f no water supply and roads\nund trulls developed for the use of\nstockmen.\n\u201cLive stock management on both\nrange and ranch, prevention of loss\nes, ranch managements, diseases und\ncontrol, predatory animal control\nand klndered question were all given\nconsideration and the result of in\nvestlgnllon along these lines will be\ngiven In a hand bpok to lie Issued.\n\u201cDairying und nulrltlo.n were also\nsubjects taken up In connection with\nthe live stock Issues, It being the\nIdea to link up these projects with\nlive stock and range activities for\n(he betterment of the service of\nwhich they form a part. Prof. K. V.\nScott, dairy specialist, represented\nNevada In the Interests If dairying, j\nand Miss Mary E. Stilwell spoke of\nthe Interests of nutrition.\nOTTO LINK RECEIVES\nHAD NEWS FROM GERMANY\nOtto Unk this week received a\nleter frcyn Germany telling of the\ndeath of his mother, which occurred\nearly In November.\nThe Everett orchestra will give\nthe second of a series of social\ndances at Masonic hall Saturday\nnight.\nAnnual Stockholders Meeting\nThe Twelfth Annual Meeting of\nthe stockholders of The I nlted\nfanners\u2019 Telephone and Telegraph j\nCompany, will be held in Odd Kel-|\nlows' Hall, Gardnervflle, Nevada, on\nSaturday, December 1, 1933, at 1\no'clock p. m\u201e for the purpose of\nelecting officers for the ensuing\nyear and the transaction of such\nother business as mny properly come\nbefore the meeting.\nThe t'nlted farmers' Tel. ,A Tel. Co.\nE. J. PHILLIPS, Secretary.\nMANY WOULD\nEVADE AUTO TAX\nTraffic Officer Rounds\nUp Delinquents in\nNevada\nThe campaign of enforcement of\nthe motor vehicle license law in\naugurated hy this department in\nJuly has served to make this a record\nyear in the number t\\f licenses is\nsued and fees collected, says (lie Ne\nvada Highway News. Up to No\nvember 20th the Secretary of State's\noffice lias registered 15,542 cars and\nlicense fee collections to that date\n(amounted to \u00bb166,4.12.48.\nThe special traffic officer assigned\nto this w\u00ab\\rk by the state highway\ndepartment up to November 9th had\ncompelled delinquent motorists to\nlake out licenses to the number of\n>2 and had collected in fees on ac\neo,unt of the foregoing licenses the\nsum of $7,248.16.\nThe total license collections for j\n1922 were $108,944.52; therefore, to!\ndate 1921 shows an Increase over;\n1922 of $47,487.96 or approximately\n14 per cent After deduction of the i\nexpenses of the Secretary of State's\noffice In connection with the Is\nsuance of license plates and the de-'\njductlon of the amount required to\nmeet honil Interest due in 1923 the 1\n1 balance will he transferred to the\nstate highway fund for expenditures\ndirect on road construction anil i\nmaintenance. This will give the de\npartment a fund of approximately\n11115,000 from this source based on J\nreceipt* to date. Some increase, j\nhowever, will be shown before the\nend of the calendar year Inasmuch\nas the enforcement officers are still\nin the field.\nIt seems hard to believe that some\nof the citizens of Nevada would go j\nto such extremes In avoiding the pay-'\nmi nt of such a small tux as that 1\nrepresented by the automobile license\nfee. In many cases violations have\nbeen so flagrant that the officers have\nbeen compelled to arrest the offend\ners and hale them into court for\ntrial. Every case of this sort has\nresulted In a fine of aprpoximately\n|M) In addition to the payment of the\nregular license fee. These violators\nwill lie closely watched during the\nnext year and inasmuch as the de\npartment will have a complete record\nof all cars licensed during the pres\nent year it seems probable that those\nwho escape payment of the fee next\nyear will be very limited In number.\nII'TOMOBII.KS WEKK NOT\nI\u2019OITIAK IN 1901 AS NOW\n\"There is some difference in the\nattitude eoward automobile today j\nand the attitude in 1901,\" says James\nK Peckham, Nevada pioneer and a\nresident of Reno. reports the\nGazette. \u201cRecently I noticed where\nthe state highway dept -tment had Is\nsued an order to keep stock off the\nhighways and the special danger on\nthe Reno-Carson highway is men\ntioned in the order.\" he continued\n\"No,w In 1901 when 1 was In the\nlegislature a bill was Introduced\nwhich provided than any owner or\ndriver of an automobile on the slate\nhighways who saw a team or horse\ndrawn wagon approaching. must j\ndrive to one side of the road, stop\nhis engine and not start until the I\nteam was safely past\n\"I was under the Impression that\nthis bill passed but now I can find j\nno record of it. At any rate, there\nwas considerable feeling expressed\nagainst people who would drive a\nnoisy vehicle along a highway frlght\n\"nlng teams.\"\n\u00bbii in an civil, from\nSOITIIFIlN I Flint TO COAST\nI\nI .os Angeles is getting busy and a\ncorps of engineers are now out\nI stalking the jungle wastes in search\nof a canal route from lkmlder Can\nion to the City of Angeles, through\nwhich aqueduct a large part of the\nJ How of the Colorado river Is lo be\ntaken. Along this route will be\ngieat sellling basins, drops where\nI power will be generated and diver\nsions of the water into fields that\nmay be made fertile by the Introduc\ntion cf water. At least that is the\ndream of the men at the head of af\nfairs having to do with the water\nand power situation In Los Angeles.\n1.1 THEBAN CHCIICII NOTES\nSaturday, Dec. 1. No confirmutl<>u\nclass, but the Sunday School meets\nat p. m. for rehersal on the Christ\nmas program. An excellent program\nis in preparation, but we will navi\nto have the hearty cooperation ol\nall the scholars of the school in\norder to make it successful. Parents\nwill please send their children for\npractice regularly, every time.\nSunday, Dec. 2.\u2014The first Sunday\nin Advent, beginning a new church\nyear. English worship af 10:30 a\nhi., German at 2 p. tn. Subject:\n\u201cOur Hosanna'\" Holy communion j\nwill be celebrated in the morning\nservice, announcement for which\nwill kindly he made Friday after\nnoon and evening. This does not\nmean that this will he a service for\ncommunicants only, so begin the new\neccllesiustical year properly, with\nworship of the Advent King\nWednesday. Dec. 5.\u2014Meeting of\nthe church hoard. See the treasurer\nbefore this date.\nThursday, Dec. 6.\u2014Meeting of the\nMissionary Ladles' Aid.\nTo all who worship with us, seek\ning truth and the way to eternal\nlife, Trinity Church extends a\ncordial welcome.\nPAUL II. FELTEN, Pastor.\nXMAS SEALS ARE I\nNOW ON SALE;\nNevada People Asked1\nto Give Generously\nto Good Cause\n_ i\nTile Nevada Public Health Associa\ntion has one' million Christmas Seals\nfor sale. The distribution and sale\nof these seals will begin December!\nj 1st. Over snot) letters are to bej\nniailed; these letters containing\nseals and a report of the work done\nin the past year.\nInto every corner of Neva^\nthroughout the past six years these\nseals of the Tuberculosis Association\nhave carried a two-fold message to\nthe afflicted that tuberculosis may be\ncured; to the well that it can be\nprevented. They have preached by\nprecept and practice the simple gos\npel, as simple at the (Icldcn Rule of\nthe Nazarene, of wholesome good,\nsunshine, fresh air, sleep, rest, poise\nof mind, cleanliness of soul as of\nbody and complete normality in\neverything.\nNevada tied California in Belling\nseals last year and was the fourth\nstate in the Union selling the great\nest number of seals per capita. Ne\nvada's average was 5.3.\nNEW FIRE CHIEF\nNOW IN CHARGE\nA volunteer lire department has\nteen organized at Minden, Wm.\nWennhold being elected chief of the\nnew organization. A few days ago\nthe members were give instructions\nin the operation of the chemical en\ngine and other apparatus owned by\nthe department.\nDuring the past summer property\nholders of Minden erected a sub\nstantial brick building for housing\nthe fire equipment and have also\nco-operated in the organization <\\f\na fire department.\nFire hydrants have been placed in\nall parts of the town and through\nthe installation of three powerful\nelectric pumps and storage tanks\na high pressure can be maintained\nin the pipe linos almost indefinitely.\nThis, coupled with the chemical en\ngine, gives Minden adequate fire\nprotection.\nmm: he\\hs kicked in\nItKIlMJEPOHT SECTION\nDuring the past six weeks bear\nhunting has been the real sport\naround Bridgeport, the Mono county\nseat The bears had become tame\nor were off their traveled territory,\nfor three large bruins wee killed on\nthe meadows where thousands of cat\ntle were pasturing Six more larger\nblack bears were killed in the foot\nhills, not over four miles from\nBridgeport, it is thought that the\nhears followed the Tioga ro.ad com\ning from Yosemite Valley. There\nhasn\u2019t been a bear killed in the\nvicinity of Bridgeport for several\nye,it past and old trappers are puz\nzled as to the cause of their presence\nin such large numbers.\nunirACTOii iron at\nllltIDHKPOKT KKSEKVOIK\nEngineer J. A. Iieemer, of the\nWalker River Irrigation District, who\nwas a visitor at Bridgeport last\nWednesday ami Thursday, reports\ni very satisfactory progress being\nmade on the construction of the stor\nage reservoir on the East Walker, re\nports the Maso.n Valley News. He\nstates that the concrete work is go\ning along nicely and that, should the\npresent favorable weather continue\nthat in all likllhood the concrete\nwc\\rk will have been finished before\nit is nccc-sary to stop w'ork for the\ni winter.\nEKO MEN ARE\nTO BE ARRESTED\nAs predicted in the Elko Free\nPress some time ag<*fl the house\ncleaning of the Elko booze dispen\nsaries, operating in violation of the\neighteenth amendment, is due to\nlake place some time during the\npresent week, according tq tniorma\ntion received in Elko today, says the\nFree Press Contained in this in\nformation is the statement that 26\ncriminal informations involving 31\npersons and charging violation of the\nnational prohibition act have been\nprepared by the United States dis\ntrict attorney and will be died with\nProhibition Director J. P. Donnelley\nin Reno.\nIt is also stated in the infi\\rmation\nthat abatement proceedings are be\ning prepared against practically all\nof the offenders, which means that\ntheir quarters will be closed to any\ntype of business for periods ranging\nfrom six to eighteen months, depend\ning o,n the federal attorney.\nSTRAWBERRIES IT FALLON\nFOR THANKSGIVING\nFresh strawberries from home\ngardens are in prospect for the\nThanksgiving dinner at a few ranch\nes near Fallo.n. for everbearing\nstrawberries are continuing to rlpetf\nin protected spots, reports the Fallon\nEagle.\nPoplar trees that have Just shed\ntheir sinner foliage are beginning to\nI bud here. A new crop t\\f California\n1 poppies in beds are again blooming.\nBIJOU TELEPHONE\nLINE BOUGHT BY\nFARMERS CO.\nThe United Farmers\u2019 Telephone i-.\nTelegraph company, tnrough its\nmanager, E. J. Phillips, recently\nclosed a deal for the purchase <*f the\nprivately owned toil line extending\nfrom the foot of Kingusbury grade\nto hake Tahoe. This line was built\nby Young Bros, and Jack Meyn ttf\nBijou several yearB ago and Its sale\nto the Farmers\u2019 company is for the\npurpose of bringing about better\ntelephone service between Gardner\nville and hake Tahoe pt\\ints.\nDuring the past week the Farmers'\ncompany has had a crew of linemen\nat work overhauling the line and put\nting It in first class condition for\nwinter.\nSince the line has been repaired\nseveral long distance calls between\n\u25a0san Francisco and Bijou have been\nmade with excellent results a serv\nice that is greately appreciated by\nhake Tahoe residents.\nThe telephone line between Tallac\nand Truckee Is hard to keep in work\ning order during big storms, while\nlittle or no difficulty has been ex\nperienced maintaining the Gardner\nvllle-Bljou line during the winter\nmonths, and serves practically all of\nthe inhabitants at the south end of\nl-ake Tahoe. Arrangements are n<\\w\nbeing made to extend the service to\nother resorts near Bijou and A1\nTahoe.\nSICK NEVADANS\nSECURE WHISKY\nThree thousand and seventy-eight\nsick persons in Nevada were able to\nbuy liquor in prescriptions since the\nState laws were repealed last winter\nand since the new regulations have\ngone into effect have used 364 gallons\nof whiskey, besides a smaller quan\ntity of other stimulants.\nNevada shows the smallest con\nsumption of any State where the pre\nscription system ^s legal. Wyoming\nphysiciasn issued 7048 prescriptions\non which 840 gallons of whiskey and\nsmall quantities of other alcoholic\ntonics were sold by drug stores.\nHard liquor Is not sold in Utah or\nIdaho on physicians rescriptions and.\nofficially at least, these two States\nare bone dry.\nNEW FOOD VALUE\nIN ALFALFA HAY\nAnalysis of a fine green dust sent\nto the Nevada pure food and drug\nlaboratory has resulted in the dis\ncovery of a valuable by-product to\nthe adfalfa meal Industry now under\nway at Fallon, says the Reno Journ\nal.\nThe powder-like substance is a\nsample taken from the dust collect\nors of the alfalfa meal plant. A\nchemical investigation conducted by\nCommissioner S. C. Rinsmore and\nhis assist ant, Wayne R Adams,\nshows that the alfalfa dust is rich\nin fats anl proteins, indicating that\nit will make valuable animal food.\nWhile the ordinary alfalfa meal\ncontains approximatey 35 per cent\nof crude fiber and 1.1 per cent of\nfats, an analyzatlon of the alfalfa\ndust showed It to have but 13 to 15\nper cent of crude fiber and high fat\ncontent of about five and one half\nper cent. The crude fiber, male by\ngrinding the stems of the alfalfa\nplant with leaves, is of cellulose\nand contains little food value.\nSamples were sent to the state\nlaboratory in order to ascertain the\nfood content before efforts are made\nto find a market for the product.\nSI,(IT .MACHINES ARE IN\nFI LL OPERTION IN RENO\nWhile other Nevada towns have al\nmost forgotten the form of slot ma\nchines, in which nickels, quarters\nand half dollars are played, winners\nreceiving real money in return, Reno\njs not classed in the list, and visitors\nto Nevada\u2019s metropolis, say that slot\nmachines may be found in hotel\nlobbies, cigar stores and other es\ntablishments and one has to almost\nelbow his way through the crowds\nthat gather about the machines.\nNEW YEAR\u2019S\nDANCE\nMONDAY NIGHT\nDecember 31st\nMINDEN INN\nMinden, Nevada\nBEST MUSIC\nMIDNIGHT SUPPER\nThe Sew Years' Dance at the\nMinden Inn will be the lead\ning social event of the winter\nseason and you are Invited to\nbe in attendance.\nGOOD DWAY\nON D WORK\nPower Shovel Placed\nin U\u00bbe in Work of\nGrading\nTleslau Brothers, highway con-!\ntractors, are making good headway\non the Double Springs project mid\nway between Gardnerville and Well\nington. Some thirty-eight head of\nhorses are being used in grading\nwork, while a gasoline sluy/el is\nemployed to make fills across the\nnumerous gullies beyond Carters\nstation as well as cutting down\nsmall elevations on the route.\nThe new highway calls fc\\r the in\nstallation of numerous culverts,\nmany of them having already been\nput in place.\nThus far the contractors have\nbeen favored with exceptional good\nweather for out dqor work and if\nwinter storms withhold a few more\nweeks it is believed that consider\nable of the new highway will be\nsurfaced with crushed rock and\ngravel.\nThe road now being built has, for\nyears, been o,ne of the most dreaded\nstretches on the Wellington road and\nthe completion of the new highway\nwillbe an improvement that will be\nof great benefit to the traveling\npublic.\nGERMANS MASSES\nGO HUNGRY j\n\nWhile politicians quibble and de-;\nlay, the German masses starve or\nlive on insufficient ratlqns, says a\npress dispatch. Unemployment is\ngrowing at a rapid rate and millions\nof Germans face a winter of want\nand privation.\nBerlin and other cities and towns\nhave established municipal kitchens.\nLimited quantities of free fuel are\nprovided fqr by card.\nWith the abolishment of the bread\nj card and the subsequent rise of\nGerman black bread to figures which\ni are fantastic in comparison with the\nunemployment doles, the situation be\ncome mo,re acute than ever and give\npolitical agitators their opportunity\nto incite riot.\nThe condition of the unemployed\nIs pathetic in the extreme. By de\ngress the r\\ld people, many of them\nmiddle class, have been forced to\ngo upon the street for alms.\nThe fact remains that German had\nan excellent crop this year There\nare more than enough potatoes for\nthe German public. Germany had a\nbumper cro.p of grain. But the cur\nrency crash and the let-down of\ntransportation and general disorgan\nization in the governmet have made\nit Impossible to distribute the food\nand enable the public tc\\ buy it.\nIndignation is general against all\nparties in the reichstag. Feeling is;\nhigh against leaders who have al\nlowed politics to get Into such a\njangle that politicians seem to be\nthinking only of the welfare of their\nparticular party and r\\f their own\njobs.\nAboslute neglect of domestic prob\nlems in an attempt to sole interna\nt'onal problems is the almost uni\nversal charge against the government\nwhich Stressmann suceeded. The\nparties ahe all blaming each other.\nThe -big coalition Is said by political\nleaders to have been an error. But\nthe public is in no mod to accept\nexcuses. It Is hungry and cold in a\ncountry where there is food and fuel.\nand Stresemann is looked to for\nhelp, but not with great confidence\non the part of the generad public.\nIt has been fo,ole! too often by po\nlitical promises. The proposed gold\ncurrency is looked at with distrust.\nLUTELTON MAY\nBE TRIED HERE\nThere is more than a possibility\nthat Frederick Idttelton, deposed U.\nS. naturalization officer, recently ac\nquitted in San Francisco upon the\ncharge of fraudulently issuing natur\nalization papers, will be brought tc\nNevada to stand trial in the federal\ncourt upon the charge of having ac\ncepted bribes, says the Journal.\nRobert Wright, special naturaliza\ntion officer, was an arrival in Reno\na few days ago from San Francisco\nand immediately went to work in the\noffice of County clerk Beemer. I\nWhile Mr. Wright refused to either1\naffirm or deny that he was in Reno\nin the interests of the government in\nthe charges pending against Lil<eltun\nit is known that he is hunting up\nrecords in cases where Rittelton is\nsupposed to have accepted bribes.\nIt was learned from an authorative\nsource that the government is con\ntemplating further prosecution of\nIJttelton. both in San Francisco and\nin Carson City, and it is probable\nthat the present grand jury in Carscn\nwill be presented matters pertaining\nj to the case.\nRENO HUNTERS KILE\nEI01IT HUNDRED RABBITS\nj _\nAbout eight hundred rabbits were\nj delivered to the Salvation Army at\nReno fo,r distribution v'nong many\nfamilies fer Thanksgiving as a re\nsult of the annual rabbit drive held\nby Reno hunters a few days ago.\nRabbits were not found as plenti\nful as last year, the hunters report\nSPECIAL CAR\nFOR PRISONERS\nBootleg Special Leaves\nReno for Federal\nPrison\nTuesday night U. S. Marshal J. H.\nFulmer, Deputy Marshal G. U Plum\nmer and a number of guards left\nKeno in charge of twenty federal\nprlsoneds, nineteen of whom will be\nplaced in the government prison at\nI.eavonworth, Kansas. The twcnty\nieth prisoner, Jospeh Keller, will be\ntaken to New York, where he will\nface charges arising from his con\nnection with bankruptcy matters in\nfederal court in one of the New York\ndistricts.\nA Pullman car especially equip\npcn was used to transport the prison\ners. A porter and a cook was as\nsigned to the bootleg special.\nGuards selected by Marshal Ful\nmer were SherlfT Joe Stern of Orms\nby county, Joe Nenzel, Joe Kirkley,\nFrank Wheeler L. G. Clark, Joe\nHoopes and G. B. Spradltng.\nThe prisoners making up the car\nloah were:\nWilliam Murphy, 18 months; Ttpn\nWalker, 13 months. F. M. Lincoln.\n26 months; 0. F. Park, 24 months;\nI). E. Clark, 24 months; Paul Col\nlins, 12 months; Joe Gonsales, 15\nmonths, Joe Yama, 3 years; Chum\nLung. 15 mo,nths, Jim Sing, 2 years;\nJung Wing, 2 years; Eugene Murphy,\n13 months, Emil Schmidt, 15 months;\nYee Hee, 2 years; Tim Jim, 2 years;\nQuon Soo, 3 years, two counts, sen\ntences to run uncurrently; Dick Wah\n22 months: Charlie Hong, 5 years.\nGeorge Butler was sentenceh to\nserve 16 mo.nths in Leavenworth for\nviolation of the Mann act, but he\nmade his escape a few moments af\nter he and thirty-odd prisoners start\ned from the railroad station to the\njail at Reno, and so far he has been\nable to avoid capture, says the Car\nson News.\nMOKE JOB SEEKERS\nTHAN JOBS IN NEVADA\nThere are twice as many men\nseeking jobs as there are jobs for\nthem, if conditions at the federal\nemployment office in Reno are typic\nal c\\f the entire Nevada employment\nsituation, according to the Journal.\nW. A. Burns, in charge of the Reno\nirffice, attributes the shortage of p<\\bs\nto the shutting down of lumber mills\nat Verdi, Loyalton and adjacent\nt owns, the inactivity of Nevada\nmines at present and the fact that\nthe hiring of farm labor has prac\ntically ceased for the year.\nVALLEY HAY\nTO BE GRADED\nIn order to establish a hay grad\ning and inspection system in the hay\ngrowing centers of the state, San\nford commissioner and head of the\ngrading service established by the\nlast state legislature, is visiting\nLovelock, Yerlngton and other towns\nin Pershing. Lyon and Douglas\ncounties.\nRanchers of the region are said to\nbe heartily in favor of the inspect\nion system, and the appointment of\nan inspector, similar to the one em\nployed for the grading and inspection\nof Nevada potatoes, is practically\nassured.\nFrederick W. Wilson, professor of\nanimal husbandry at the University\nof Nevada, accompanied Commission\ner Dinsntore on part of his tour and\nassisted in explaining the grading\nsystem to the hay growers.\nAlthough a quarantine against the\nshipment of hay from several Ne\nvada counties is enforced by Cali\nfornia, growers in central and parts\nof western Nevada have found a\ngood market with Kansas City deal\ners. The Nevada hay enjoys the dis\ntinction o,f being one of the best\ngrades in the market, about CO per\ncen, of the product rating as choice,\nand the other 40 per cent, the grade\nknown as U. S. No. 1.\u2014Journal.\nSUGAR BEET MEN\nVISIT VA1 EY\nFarmers Here Urged\nto Engage in Sugai\nBeet Culture\nMr. Kline and Madison, represent\ning the Cooperative Sugar fleet Co.,\nqf Fallon, were in Carson Valley\nMonday looking over the situation\nhere for the purpose of interesting\nfarmers to plant at least a small\nacreage to sugar beets during the\ncoming season.\nThe gentlemen stated that an acre\nqf ground In this section would pro\nduce on the average of 15 tens of\nbeets, and with sugar selling at six\ncents the returns to the farmer\nwould be better than $200 to the\nacre.\nUnder the new plan the Sugar com\npany would contract with the farmer\nfqr the cultivation of the beets by\nimporting exerlenced workers, thus\nsolving the labor question. To oper\nate the plant at Fallon next season,\nat least 5000 acres must be planted\nto beets in Western Nevada.\nThe small acreage sqlicited in Car\nson Valley Is mainly for the purpose\nof demonstrating to the farmers the\nadvantages of sugar beet culture.\nThe representatives of the Fallon\ncompany declared that at elast five\nfactqrles would be built by that con\ncern in Nevada within the next three\nor four years. East factory will dis\ntribute approximately $2,000,000 and\nunders such conditions would be of\ngreat benefit to the state and to the\nagricultural Interests.\nIt the required acreage be secured\nin Carson Valley, in all probability\none of the big factories would be lo\ncated here, and in that event the\ndistribution of a n\u201c.llon or so dollars\nannually would do much toward the\nreturn of prosperity, as It has been\nstated.\nMr. Kline and Madison spent a day\nor so getting In touch with farmers\nhere and their future endeavor de\npends upon the encouragement met.\nDinner Party At\nH. Codecke Home\nMr. and Mrs. Henry Godecke, Jr.,\ngave a dinner party at their home\nlast Sunlay evening to a number qf\ntheir friends. The dining room was\nappropriately decorated with autumn\nleaves and Thanksgiving favors were\nused.\nSeated at the attractive table with\nthe host and hostess were the Misses\nElds Fricke, Ada Fricke. Helen\nCordes, Alvina Hussman, Erna God\necke, Arthur Cordes, Wm. 1-angc,\nChris Cordes, Harold Hussman and\nGeorge Cordes.\nGASOLINE TAX RETURNS\nCLOSE TO #100,OIH)\nOctober receipts from the state\ngasoline tax of two cents a gallon\nwill bring the total derived from\nthat source so far this year cIobo to\n$100,000 and with two months\u2019 more\nre turns to be made It is expected\nthat close to $120,000 will have been\ncollected since the law went Into\nefTect on March 20th.\nUp to October 1 the amount re\nceived by the state was $84,092.33 and\nfor October the following returns\nhave been made: Standard Oil Co.,\n$8068.72; Union Oil Co.. $2528.74; As\nsociated Oil Ccy, $1116.48; Shell Co..\n688.78, L. B. Jenkins. Importer of\nReno. $313.16; O. M. Doty of Moapa,\n$173.28; E. W. Shirk of Beatty $54.94;\nKred Remmlck, of Beatty $40.76.\nNOTICE TO TAXPAYERS\nNotice is hereby given t a\u2019 the\nfit si installment of taxes is now due\nand payable to the Couu\u2019.\u2019 Clerk, at\nbit office In Mlndcti. If not paid on\nor before Monday December 3d.\n1923, they will become id. iquent.\nH. R. JEPSEN. Clerk.\nMEHHODIST CHURCH SERVICES\nSunday School Sunday morning at\n10 a. nt.\nPreaching at 11 a. in\nEpworth l eague at 7:30 p. 'n.\nAll are cordially Invited.\nE. V. BRONSON, Pastor.\nPay by CHECK\nWhen robberies and holdups are\nso prevalent, take care to have as\nlittle cash as possible about the\nhome or on the person.\nOpen a checking account and let\nthis bank guard your money.\nThen pay your bills by check. It\nis the safe and convenient way.\nCome in and let us expain the\nmany advantages.\nFarmers Bank of Carson Valley, Inc.\nMniden, Nevada","height":"25816","width":"19552"}}
